  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There have been several significant legal precedents in money laundering cases, including:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1985)\n- First major corporate conviction for money laundering\n- Established corporate criminal liability for failing to report suspicious transactions\n\n2. United States v. BCCI (1991)\n- Large-scale international money laundering case\n- Demonstrated complex cross-border financial criminal activities\n\n3. United States v. Romer (2000)\n- Clarified intent requirements for money laundering prosecutions\n- Established that prosecutors must prove deliberate financial transactions\n\n4. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Expanded legal definitions of money laundering\n- Increased regulatory reporting requirements\n\n5. Basel Committee Recommendations\n- International standards for anti-money laundering procedures\n- Influenced global financial regulation frameworks\n\nThese cases and guidelines have shaped contemporary legal approaches to investigating and prosecuting money laundering activities. Each precedent contributed to developing more sophisticated legal mechanisms for detecting and preventing financial crimes.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering legal precedents?",
